## 3 Question 1 - a : What does the distribution of LungCap look like? (Hint: Plot a histogram with probability density on the y axis)

The distribution of LungCap looks as follows:

```{r, echo=T}
hist(df$LungCap)
```

The histogram suggests that the distribution is close to a normal 
distribution. Most of the observations are close to the mean. Very 
few observations are close to the margins (0 and 15).

## Question 1 - b : Compare the probability distribution of the LungCap with respect to Males and Females? (Hint: make boxplots separated by gender using the boxplot() function)

```{r}
ggplot(df, aes(x = LungCap)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  facet_wrap(~ Gender, nrow = 1)
```

```{r}
ggplot(df, aes(x = LungCap)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  facet_wrap(~ Gender, nrow = 1)
```

Both the histogram and bar plot suggests that, the distribution of 
'LungCap' for 'female' is close to normal distribution with more 
observations close to mean and fewer observations far from mean.
While the graphs of 'LungCap' for 'male' suggests that, distribution
of the observations is more close to left skewed or negative skewed. 

## Question 1 -c : Compare the mean lung capacities for smokers and non-smokers. Does it make sense?

```{r}
t_test_result <- t.test(LungCap ~ Smoke, data = df)
t_test_result
```

For my perspective, the data doesn't make any sense. The fact that 
smoking damages the operation and the capacity of lungs, doesn't 
seems to be valid for this data. In fact, this data proves that 
not smoking is dangerous to lungs(which is totally wrong). We 
should also consider that, the capacity of lungs is a natural 
thing and varies from person to person. There is a chance that 
even if a person does smoking still their lungs are not much 
affected by it. And, unluckily the randomize of the sampling 
have chosen those samples.

## Question 1 - d : Examine the relationship between Smoking and Lung Capacity within age groups: “less than or equal to 13”, “14 to 15”, “16 to 17”, and “greater than or equal to 18”.

```{r}
df = mutate(df, AgeCat = case_when(
  Age <= 13 ~ '<= 13',
  Age == 14 ~ '14 to 15',
  Age == 15 ~ '14 to 15',
  Age == 16 ~ '16 to 17',
  Age == 17 ~ '16 to 17',
  Age >= 18 ~ '>= 18'
))
```

```{r}
ggplot(df, aes(x = LungCap)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  facet_grid(AgeCat ~ Gender)
```

```{r}
ggplot(df, aes(x = LungCap)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  facet_grid(AgeCat ~ Gender)
```

For both males and females, the age group '<= 13' shows the widest 
distribution of lung capacity, suggesting greater variability in this 
group.  The age groups '14-15', '16-17', and '>= 18', reveal a trend of 
decreasing lung capacity counts, particularly for females.  
Males, however, maintain a more consistent distribution across 
these older age groups, though with a slight decrease in the 
'>= 18' group. Overall, the histograms suggest that lung capacity 
distribution is influenced by both age and gender, with younger 
individuals showing more variation and males demonstrating a more 
stable distribution across older age categories compared to females.

